WALLETS

CRYPTOCURRENCY WALLETS
A cryptocurrency wallet is a software or hardware tool used to store private keys, which provide ownership and access to digital assets on a blockchain.
 Note: Wallets do not store coins; they store private and public keys.

HOT WALLET (Online Wallet)
Definition
A Hot Wallet is a cryptocurrency wallet that is connected to the internet, allowing quick and easy access to digital assets.

How It Works
Private keys are stored in online software
Transactions are signed and broadcast online
Direct interaction with blockchain networks

Types of Hot Wallets
Mobile wallets (Trust Wallet, MetaMask)
Web wallets (Exchange wallets like Binance, Coinbase)
Desktop wallets (Exodus)





Hot Wallet ‚Äì Key Aspects
Aspect
Description
Security Mechanism
Password protection, Two-Factor Authentication (2FA), encryption, seed phrase backup
Advantages
Fast access, easy to use, suitable for frequent transactions
Disadvantages
Higher exposure to hacking, phishing, and malware
Real-World Use Case
Daily payments, crypto trading, DeFi platforms, NFT transactions


COLD WALLET (Offline Wallet)
Definition
A Cold Wallet is a cryptocurrency wallet that stores private keys offline, disconnected from the internet.

How It Works
Private keys are generated and stored offline
Transactions are signed offline and then broadcast online
No direct internet exposure

Types of Cold Wallets
Hardware wallets (Ledger, Trezor)
Paper wallets
Air-gapped systems

 Cold Wallet ‚Äì Key Aspects
Aspect
Description
Security Mechanism
Offline key storage, PIN/passphrase protection, tamper-resistant hardware
Advantages
Very high security, safe from online attacks, ideal for long-term holding
Disadvantages
Slower transactions, risk of physical loss or damage
Real-World Use Case
Long-term investment, institutional storage, treasury management


